GEMINI-CLI(1)              User Commands              GEMINI-CLI(1)

NAME
    gemini-cli - Bash terminal interface for the Gemini API

SYNOPSIS
    gemini-cli
    gemini-cli <session_name>
    gemini-cli --resume <session_name>
    gemini-cli --list
    gemini-cli --rename-session <old> <new>
    gemini-cli --models [--all]
    gemini-cli --update-models
    gemini-cli --test-model <model_id> [--save]
    gemini-cli --select-model [--save]
    gemini-cli --config
    gemini-cli --set <key> <value>
    gemini-cli --unset <key>
    gemini-cli --set-api-key
    gemini-cli --forget-api-key
    gemini-cli --show-memory <session_name>
    gemini-cli --edit-memory <session_name>
    gemini-cli --clear-memory <session_name>
    gemini-cli --editor-prompt [session_name]
    gemini-cli --attach <file> [session_name]
    gemini-cli --credits
    gemini-cli --version
    gemini-cli --help
    gemini-cli -h

DESCRIPTION
    gemini-cli is a lightweight Bash-based terminal chat interface for
    the Google Gemini API.

    It is the minimal, line-oriented edition of the gemini-terminal-tools
    project. It remains scriptable and dependency-light while keeping feature
    parity with the ncurses edition where that parity makes sense in a shell.

    It provides:
        - persistent chat sessions
        - named and resumable conversations
        - timestamped logs
        - rolling conversation context
        - resume-time context rebuild from session logs
        - context snapshots stored in session logs
        - temporary Project Lead startup notice for new blank sessions
        - config file support
        - line-oriented config/options commands
        - automatic code attachment extraction
        - local file attachment support
        - generated inlineData attachment saving where returned by the API
        - cached model list support
        - metadata-based model filtering
        - model listing
        - user-operated model testing
        - numbered model selection
        - API-key setup and removal helpers
        - external editor prompt support

USAGE
    First-time setup:

        gemini-cli --set-api-key
        gemini-cli --update-models
        gemini-cli --select-model

    Start a normal timestamped chat:

        gemini-cli

    Start a named chat:

        gemini-cli android-backup

    Resume a named chat:

        gemini-cli --resume android-backup

    List saved chats:

        gemini-cli --list

    Rename a session:

        gemini-cli --rename-session old-name new-name

    Refresh the model cache from Google:

        gemini-cli --update-models

    List filtered cached models:

        gemini-cli --models

    List all cached models without filters:

        gemini-cli --models --all

    Test one model:

        gemini-cli --test-model gemini-2.5-flash

    Test one model and save it if successful:

        gemini-cli --test-model gemini-2.5-flash --save

    Choose a model manually:

        gemini-cli --select-model

    Show current config/options summary:

        gemini-cli --config

    Set a config value:

        gemini-cli --set CONTEXT_TURNS 20

    Remove a config value:

        gemini-cli --unset MODEL

    Compose one prompt in an external editor:

        gemini-cli --editor-prompt mysession

    Attach a local file to the next prompt:

        gemini-cli --attach notes.txt mysession

SESSION MANAGEMENT
    gemini-cli
        Start a new timestamped session.

    gemini-cli <name>
        Start or open a named session. If the named log already exists,
        gemini-cli rebuilds recent conversation context from it.

    gemini-cli --resume <name>
        Resume an existing named session. If the session does not exist,
        the command exits with an error.

    gemini-cli --rename-session <old> <new>
        Rename a session log.

    gemini-cli --list
        List saved sessions.

INPUT
    The Bash version uses a multiline Ctrl+D send workflow.

    Type or paste input, then press Ctrl+D to submit it.

    Ctrl+C exits the running chat.

STARTUP NOTICE
    In a new blank session, gemini-cli can display a temporary transcript-style
    Project Lead notice from remfan1994.

    Notice text:

        I strongly encourage everyone to get cruetly-free VEGETARIAN food and
        remember the 'bloodguilt' curse from the Bible.  -Project Lead,
        remfan1994

    Behavior:
        - shown only in new blank sessions
        - removed from the visible terminal when the first message is sent
        - not written to the session log
        - not sent to Gemini
        - not stored in conversation memory

    Config key:

        STARTUP_NOTICE=1

    Disable with:

        STARTUP_NOTICE=0

MODEL CACHE
    gemini-cli stores the model list cache at:

        ~/.config/gemini-cli/models-cache.json

    Refresh the cache with:

        gemini-cli --update-models

    The --models and --select-model commands use the cache when available.
    If no cache exists, gemini-cli attempts to create one.

MODEL DISCOVERY
    Available Gemini models can be listed with:

        gemini-cli --models

    They can also be listed directly with curl:

        curl "https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/v1beta/models?key=YOUR_API_KEY"

    gemini-cli filters the returned list using metadata such as
    supportedGenerationMethods, inputTokenLimit, and outputTokenLimit.

MODEL FILTERS
    The following config keys control model filtering:

        MODEL_FILTER_GENERATE_CONTENT
            If enabled, show only models reporting generateContent support.
            Default: 1

        MODEL_FILTER_REQUIRE_TOKENS
            If enabled, require nonzero input and output token metadata.
            Default: 0

        MODEL_FILTER_HIDE_PREVIEW
            If enabled, hide preview/experimental-looking models.
            Default: 0

        MODEL_MIN_INPUT_TOKENS
            Minimum input token limit required.
            Default: 0

        MODEL_MIN_OUTPUT_TOKENS
            Minimum output token limit required.
            Default: 0

        MODEL_SORT_ORDER
            Sort order for model listings.
            Supported values include:
                name
                display
                input_desc
                output_desc

MODEL TESTING
    Autoscan has been removed from the Bash version.

    Instead of probing every available model, gemini-cli tests only a
    user-selected model.

    From the shell:

        gemini-cli --test-model <model_id>

    The tester sends MODEL_TEST_PROMPT to the selected model and prints the
    raw response. The user reads the response and decides whether the model is
    useful.

    To save a model after a successful test:

        gemini-cli --test-model <model_id> --save

    The removed autoscan command:

        gemini-cli --autoscan-model

    exits with an explanation and points users toward --models, --test-model,
    and --select-model.

MODEL SELECTION
    A numbered model selection menu is available:

        gemini-cli --select-model

    The tool prints cached/filtered models, asks the user to choose a number,
    offers to test the selected model, then offers to save the chosen MODEL
    value to the config file.

    To save without a second confirmation prompt:

        gemini-cli --select-model --save

OPTIONS AND CONFIG
    The Bash version does not imitate the ncurses w3m-style options form.
    Instead, it provides line-oriented equivalents:

        gemini-cli --config
        gemini-cli --set KEY VALUE
        gemini-cli --unset KEY

    This keeps the Bash version capability-equivalent while preserving its
    scriptable command-line nature.

API KEY SETUP
    API key may be supplied by environment variable:

        export GEMINI_API_KEY=your_key

    It may also be placed in the config file:

        GEMINI_API_KEY=your_key

    gemini-cli can prompt for and save the key:

        gemini-cli --set-api-key

    Remove a config-file API key:

        gemini-cli --forget-api-key

    Saving the API key stores it in plaintext. The script attempts to chmod
    the config file to 0600.

CONFIGURATION
    Configuration file:

        ~/.config/gemini-cli/config

    Format:

        KEY=VALUE

    Supported keys include:

        MODEL
        CONTEXT_TURNS
        HISTORY_LIMIT
        GEMINI_API_KEY
        SESSION_DIR
        ATTACHMENT_DIR
        MODEL_TEST_PROMPT
        STARTUP_NOTICE
        MODEL_FILTER_GENERATE_CONTENT
        MODEL_FILTER_REQUIRE_TOKENS
        MODEL_FILTER_HIDE_PREVIEW
        MODEL_MIN_INPUT_TOKENS
        MODEL_MIN_OUTPUT_TOKENS
        MODEL_SORT_ORDER
        MAX_ATTACHMENT_BYTES
        EDITOR

    HISTORY_LIMIT is a legacy alias for CONTEXT_TURNS.

ENVIRONMENT
    GEMINI_API_KEY
        Preferred API key source.

    VISUAL
    EDITOR
        Used by --editor-prompt and --edit-memory when EDITOR is not set in
        the config file.

FILES
    ~/.config/gemini-cli/config
        Configuration file.

    ~/.config/gemini-cli/models-cache.json
        Cached Google model list.

    SESSION_DIR/*.log
        Session log files.

    ATTACHMENT_DIR/
        Extracted code block attachments and generated inlineData attachments.

ATTACHMENT SYSTEM
    Markdown fenced code blocks returned by Gemini are extracted from terminal
    display and saved into ATTACHMENT_DIR.

    Local files can be attached with:

        gemini-cli --attach FILE [session]

    Text-like files are included as text parts. Binary/media files are sent as
    Gemini REST inlineData-style request parts where supported.

    Generated inlineData response parts are saved into ATTACHMENT_DIR when
    returned by the model/API.

    Compatibility depends on model capability, file MIME type, size limits,
    and API support.

MEMORY MODEL
    gemini-cli keeps a rolling conversation context in memory.

    CONTEXT_TURNS controls how many recent user/assistant exchanges are sent
    back to Gemini with each request.

    Context snapshots are stored in session logs. When rebuilding context,
    gemini-cli prefers the latest saved snapshot and falls back to recent chat
    entries if no snapshot exists.

    Memory commands:

        gemini-cli --show-memory <session>
        gemini-cli --edit-memory <session>
        gemini-cli --clear-memory <session>

EXTERNAL EDITOR
    Compose a one-shot prompt in an external editor:

        gemini-cli --editor-prompt [session]

    Editor selection order:
        1. EDITOR config key
        2. VISUAL environment variable
        3. EDITOR environment variable
        4. nano or vi if found

CREDITS
    Show credits and the Project Lead notice:

        gemini-cli --credits

LIMITATIONS
    - Requires Bash
    - Requires curl
    - Requires python3
    - Requires internet access
    - API quota restrictions apply
    - Basic terminal input only; no ncurses-style editing
    - Ctrl+D is used to send multiline input
    - Mouse and full-screen menu behavior belong to the ncurses version
    - Media attachment support depends on Gemini model/API capability
    - --test-model verifies only one selected model and does not guarantee
      overall model quality

VERSION
